### **Step 3: Move Your Files to GitHub**

#### **1. Create a Repository on GitHub Website**

1. Go to [GitHub](https://github.com/) and log in.
2. Click the **New** button (or the `+` icon in the upper-right corner) to create a repository.
3. Name your repository (e.g., `CDAC-Flask-Docker`).
4. Keep it Public/Private based on your preference, leave "Add a README" **unchecked**, and click **Create repository**.
5. Copy the unique **HTTPS repository URL** provided on the setup page (it will look like `https://github.com/your-username/CDAC-Flask-Docker.git`).

#### **2. Initialize Git and Push Files via Command Line**

Back in your terminal window (make sure you are still inside `C:\CDAC_Project`), run the following commands sequentially:

```bash
# Initialize a local Git repository
git init

# Add all files (app.py, requirements.txt, Dockerfile) to staging
git add .

# Commit your changes with an informative message
git commit -m "Initial commit: Added CDAC Flask app and Dockerfile"

# Rename the default branch to 'main'
git branch -M main

# Link your local repository to your remote GitHub repository
# (Replace the URL below with your actual copied GitHub URL)
git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/CDAC-Flask-Docker.git

# Push your code to GitHub
git push -u origin main

```

Once completed, refresh your GitHub repository page in the browser to view your uploaded project files.


